hink that gcc warns if we were to support %08pR, so we can't <br />pass down flags.<br /><br />That said, I don't much like SPECIAL in the flags. We never do that thing. <br />Doing a git grep for some range printouts, we tend to do things like<br /><br />	[%lx,%lx]<br />	[%x - %x]<br />	[%llx, %llx]<br />	[%016lx - %016lx]<br />	&lt;%016llx-%016llx&gt;<br /><br />But using "0x%llx" or "%#llx" is very rare. It happens (notably <br />drivers/pci/setup-res.c), but it's not common.<br /><br />But it would be kind of nice to be able to do extended flags. Maybe we <br />could do it with<br /><br />	%p04R<br /><br />and the 04 would be parsed as flags, the same way we do %04x. And then if <br />you want the 0x, you can use %p#08R..<br /><br />			Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
